devdoc.details: Common mathematical functions used in both PRBMathSD59x18 and PRBMathUD60x18. Note that this shared library does not always assume the signed 59.18-decimal fixed-point or the unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point representation. When it does not, it is explicitly mentioned in the NatSpec documentation.

SCALE.details: How many trailing decimals can be represented.

SCALE_LPOTD.details: Largest power of two divisor of SCALE.

abs(int256).details: Requirements: - x must be greater than MIN_SD59x18.

params.x: The number to calculate the absolute value for.
The first operand as a signed 59.18-decimal fixed-point number.
params.y: The second operand as a signed 59.18-decimal fixed-point number.

returns.result: The arithmetic average as a signed 59.18-decimal fixed-point number.

ceil(int256).details: Optimized for fractional value inputs, because for every whole value there are (1e18 - 1) fractional counterparts. See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Floor_and_ceiling_functions. Requirements: - x must be less than or equal to MAX_WHOLE_SD59x18.

params.result: The least integer greater than or equal to x, as a signed 58.18-decimal fixed-point number.
params.x: The signed 59.18-decimal fixed-point number to ceil.

div(int256,int256).details: Variant of "mulDiv" that works with signed numbers. Works by computing the signs and the absolute values separately. Requirements: - All from "PRBMath.mulDiv". - None of the inputs can be MIN_SD59x18. - The denominator cannot be zero. - The result must fit within int256. Caveats: - All from "PRBMath.mulDiv".

params.result: The quotient as a signed 59.18-decimal fixed-point number.
params.x: The numerator as a signed 59.18-decimal fixed-point number.
params.y: The denominator as a signed 59.18-decimal fixed-point number.

exp(int256).details: Based on the insight that e^x = 2^(x * log2(e)). Requirements: - All from "log2". - x must be less than 133.084258667509499441. Caveats: - All from "exp2". - For any x less than -41.446531673892822322, the result is zero.

params.x: The exponent as a signed 59.18-decimal fixed-point number.

returns.result: The result as a signed 59.18-decimal fixed-point number.

exp2(int256).details: See https://ethereum.stackexchange.com/q/79903/24693. Requirements: - x must be 192 or less. - The result must fit within MAX_SD59x18. Caveats: - For any x less than -59.794705707972522261, the result is zero.

params.x: The exponent as a signed 59.18-decimal fixed-point number.

returns.result: The result as a signed 59.18-decimal fixed-point number.

floor(int256).details: Optimized for fractional value inputs, because for every whole value there are (1e18 - 1) fractional counterparts. See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Floor_and_ceiling_functions. Requirements: - x must be greater than or equal to MIN_WHOLE_SD59x18.

params.result: The greatest integer less than or equal to x, as a signed 58.18-decimal fixed-point number.
params.x: The signed 59.18-decimal fixed-point number to floor.

frac(int256).details: Based on the odd function definition. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fractional_part

params.result: The fractional part of x as a signed 59.18-decimal fixed-point number.
params.x: The signed 59.18-decimal fixed-point number to get the fractional part of.

fromInt(int256).details: Requirements: - x must be greater than or equal to MIN_SD59x18 divided by SCALE. - x must be less than or equal to MAX_SD59x18 divided by SCALE.

params.result: The same number in signed 59.18-decimal fixed-point representation.
params.x: The basic integer to convert.

gm(int256,int256).details: Requirements: - x * y must fit within MAX_SD59x18, lest it overflows. - x * y cannot be negative.

params.x: The first operand as a signed 59.18-decimal fixed-point number.
params.y: The second operand as a signed 59.18-decimal fixed-point number.

returns.result: The result as a signed 59.18-decimal fixed-point number.

params.x: The signed 59.18-decimal fixed-point number for which to calculate the inverse.

returns.result: The inverse as a signed 59.18-decimal fixed-point number.

ln(int256).details: Based on the insight that ln(x) = log2(x) / log2(e). Requirements: - All from "log2". Caveats: - All from "log2". - This doesn't return exactly 1 for 2718281828459045235, for that we would need more fine-grained precision.

params.x: The signed 59.18-decimal fixed-point number for which to calculate the natural logarithm.

returns.result: The natural logarithm as a signed 59.18-decimal fixed-point number.

log10(int256).details: First checks if x is an exact power of ten and it stops if yes. If it's not, calculates the common logarithm based on the insight that log10(x) = log2(x) / log2(10). Requirements: - All from "log2". Caveats: - All from "log2".

params.x: The signed 59.18-decimal fixed-point number for which to calculate the common logarithm.

returns.result: The common logarithm as a signed 59.18-decimal fixed-point number.

log2(int256).details: Based on the iterative approximation algorithm. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_logarithm#Iterative_approximation Requirements: - x must be greater than zero. Caveats: - The results are not perfectly accurate to the last decimal, due to the lossy precision of the iterative approximation.

params.x: The signed 59.18-decimal fixed-point number for which to calculate the binary logarithm.

returns.result: The binary logarithm as a signed 59.18-decimal fixed-point number.

mul(int256,int256).details: Variant of "mulDiv" that works with signed numbers and employs constant folding, i.e. the denominator is always 1e18. Requirements: - All from "PRBMath.mulDivFixedPoint". - None of the inputs can be MIN_SD59x18 - The result must fit within MAX_SD59x18. Caveats: - The body is purposely left uncommented; see the NatSpec comments in "PRBMath.mulDiv" to understand how this works.

params.x: The multiplicand as a signed 59.18-decimal fixed-point number.
params.y: The multiplier as a signed 59.18-decimal fixed-point number.

returns.result: The product as a signed 59.18-decimal fixed-point number.

pow(int256,int256).details: Based on the insight that x^y = 2^(log2(x) * y). Requirements: - All from "exp2", "log2" and "mul". - z cannot be zero. Caveats: - All from "exp2", "log2" and "mul". - Assumes 0^0 is 1.

params.x: Number to raise to given power y, as a signed 59.18-decimal fixed-point number.
params.y: Exponent to raise x to, as a signed 59.18-decimal fixed-point number.

returns.result: x raised to power y, as a signed 59.18-decimal fixed-point number.

powu(int256,uint256).details: See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponentiation_by_squaring Requirements: - All from "abs" and "PRBMath.mulDivFixedPoint". - The result must fit within MAX_SD59x18. Caveats: - All from "PRBMath.mulDivFixedPoint". - Assumes 0^0 is 1.

params.x: The base as a signed 59.18-decimal fixed-point number.

returns.result: The result as a signed 59.18-decimal fixed-point number.

sqrt(int256).details: Uses the Babylonian method https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Methods_of_computing_square_roots#Babylonian_method. Requirements: - x cannot be negative. - x must be less than MAX_SD59x18 / SCALE.

params.x: The signed 59.18-decimal fixed-point number for which to calculate the square root.

returns.result: The result as a signed 59.18-decimal fixed-point .

params.x: The signed 59.18-decimal fixed-point number to convert.

returns.result: The same number in basic integer form.

LOG2_E.details: log2(e) as a signed 59.18-decimal fixed-point number.

MIN_SD59x18.details: The minimum value a signed 59.18-decimal fixed-point number can have.

MIN_WHOLE_SD59x18.details: The minimum whole value a signed 59.18-decimal fixed-point number can have.

powu(int256,uint256).notice: Raises x (signed 59.18-decimal fixed-point number) to the power of y (basic unsigned integer) using the famous algorithm "exponentiation by squaring".

scale().notice: Returns 1 as a signed 59.18-decimal fixed-point number.

sqrt(int256).notice: Calculates the square root of x, rounding down.

toInt(int256).notice: Converts a signed 59.18-decimal fixed-point number to basic integer form, rounding down in the process.

userdoc.notice: Smart contract library for advanced fixed-point math that works with int256 numbers considered to have 18 trailing decimals. We call this number representation signed 59.18-decimal fixed-point, since the numbers can have a sign and there can be up to 59 digits in the integer part and up to 18 decimals in the fractional part. The numbers are bound by the minimum and the maximum values permitted by the Solidity type int256.

params.x: The first operand as an unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number.
params.y: The second operand as an unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number.

returns.result: The arithmetic average as an unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number.

ceil(uint256).details: Optimized for fractional value inputs, because for every whole value there are (1e18 - 1) fractional counterparts. See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Floor_and_ceiling_functions. Requirements: - x must be less than or equal to MAX_WHOLE_UD60x18.

params.result: The least integer greater than or equal to x, as an unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number.
params.x: The unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number to ceil.

div(uint256,uint256).details: Uses mulDiv to enable overflow-safe multiplication and division. Requirements: - The denominator cannot be zero.

params.result: The quotient as an unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number.
params.x: The numerator as an unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number.
params.y: The denominator as an unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number.

exp(uint256).details: Based on the insight that e^x = 2^(x * log2(e)). Requirements: - All from "log2". - x must be less than 133.084258667509499441.

params.x: The exponent as an unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number.

returns.result: The result as an unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number.

exp2(uint256).details: See https://ethereum.stackexchange.com/q/79903/24693. Requirements: - x must be 192 or less. - The result must fit within MAX_UD60x18.

params.x: The exponent as an unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number.

returns.result: The result as an unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number.

floor(uint256).details: Optimized for fractional value inputs, because for every whole value there are (1e18 - 1) fractional counterparts. See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Floor_and_ceiling_functions.

params.result: The greatest integer less than or equal to x, as an unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number.
params.x: The unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number to floor.

frac(uint256).details: Based on the odd function definition https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fractional_part.

params.result: The fractional part of x as an unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number.
params.x: The unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number to get the fractional part of.

fromUint(uint256).details: Requirements: - x must be less than or equal to MAX_UD60x18 divided by SCALE.

params.result: The same number in unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point representation.
params.x: The basic integer to convert.

gm(uint256,uint256).details: Requirements: - x * y must fit within MAX_UD60x18, lest it overflows.

params.x: The first operand as an unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number.
params.y: The second operand as an unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number.

returns.result: The result as an unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number.

params.x: The unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number for which to calculate the inverse.

returns.result: The inverse as an unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number.

ln(uint256).details: Based on the insight that ln(x) = log2(x) / log2(e). Requirements: - All from "log2". Caveats: - All from "log2". - This doesn't return exactly 1 for 2.718281828459045235, for that we would need more fine-grained precision.

params.x: The unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number for which to calculate the natural logarithm.

returns.result: The natural logarithm as an unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number.

log10(uint256).details: First checks if x is an exact power of ten and it stops if yes. If it's not, calculates the common logarithm based on the insight that log10(x) = log2(x) / log2(10). Requirements: - All from "log2". Caveats: - All from "log2".

params.x: The unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number for which to calculate the common logarithm.

returns.result: The common logarithm as an unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number.

log2(uint256).details: Based on the iterative approximation algorithm. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binary_logarithm#Iterative_approximation Requirements: - x must be greater than or equal to SCALE, otherwise the result would be negative. Caveats: - The results are nor perfectly accurate to the last decimal, due to the lossy precision of the iterative approximation.

params.x: The unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number for which to calculate the binary logarithm.

returns.result: The binary logarithm as an unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number.

mul(uint256,uint256).details: See the documentation for the "PRBMath.mulDivFixedPoint" function.

params.x: The multiplicand as an unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number.
params.y: The multiplier as an unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number.

returns.result: The product as an unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number.

pow(uint256,uint256).details: Based on the insight that x^y = 2^(log2(x) * y). Requirements: - All from "exp2", "log2" and "mul". Caveats: - All from "exp2", "log2" and "mul". - Assumes 0^0 is 1.

params.x: Number to raise to given power y, as an unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number.
params.y: Exponent to raise x to, as an unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number.

returns.result: x raised to power y, as an unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number.

powu(uint256,uint256).details: See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponentiation_by_squaring Requirements: - The result must fit within MAX_UD60x18. Caveats: - All from "mul". - Assumes 0^0 is 1.

params.x: The base as an unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number.

returns.result: The result as an unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number.

sqrt(uint256).details: Uses the Babylonian method https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Methods_of_computing_square_roots#Babylonian_method. Requirements: - x must be less than MAX_UD60x18 / SCALE.

params.x: The unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number for which to calculate the square root.

returns.result: The result as an unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point .

params.x: The unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number to convert.

returns.result: The same number in basic integer form.

MAX_UD60x18.details: The maximum value an unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number can have.

MAX_WHOLE_UD60x18.details: The maximum whole value an unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number can have.

SCALE.details: How many trailing decimals can be represented.

avg(uint256,uint256).notice: Calculates the arithmetic average of x and y, rounding down.

ceil(uint256).notice: Yields the least unsigned 60.18 decimal fixed-point number greater than or equal to x.

div(uint256,uint256).notice: Divides two unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point numbers, returning a new unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number.

e().notice: Returns Euler's number as an unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number.

exp(uint256).notice: Calculates the natural exponent of x.

exp2(uint256).notice: Calculates the binary exponent of x using the binary fraction method.

floor(uint256).notice: Yields the greatest unsigned 60.18 decimal fixed-point number less than or equal to x.

frac(uint256).notice: Yields the excess beyond the floor of x.

fromUint(uint256).notice: Converts a number from basic integer form to unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point representation.

gm(uint256,uint256).notice: Calculates geometric mean of x and y, i.e. sqrt(x * y), rounding down.

ln(uint256).notice: Calculates the natural logarithm of x.

log10(uint256).notice: Calculates the common logarithm of x.

log2(uint256).notice: Calculates the binary logarithm of x.

mul(uint256,uint256).notice: Multiplies two unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point numbers together, returning a new unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number.

pi().notice: Returns PI as an unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number.

pow(uint256,uint256).notice: Raises x to the power of y.

powu(uint256,uint256).notice: Raises x (unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number) to the power of y (basic unsigned integer) using the famous algorithm "exponentiation by squaring".

scale().notice: Returns 1 as an unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number.

sqrt(uint256).notice: Calculates the square root of x, rounding down.

toUint(uint256).notice: Converts a unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point number to basic integer form, rounding down in the process.

userdoc.notice: Smart contract library for advanced fixed-point math that works with uint256 numbers considered to have 18 trailing decimals. We call this number representation unsigned 60.18-decimal fixed-point, since there can be up to 60 digits in the integer part and up to 18 decimals in the fractional part. The numbers are bound by the minimum and the maximum values permitted by the Solidity type uint256.
